<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1436,869,1552]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Frustules rectangular in girdle view, somewhat constricted in the middle. Valves broadly lanceolate, to rhombic-lanceolate, with not protracted but broadly cuneate valve ends. Valve length 
<quantity box="[1184,1354,908,934]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.9" metricValueMax="3.35" metricValueMin="2.45" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" unit="mm" value="29.0" valueMax="33.5" valueMin="24.5">24.5–33.5 µm</quantity>
, width 
<quantity box="[151,290,946,972]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.5" metricValueMax="9.5" metricValueMin="7.5" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" unit="mm" value="8.5" valueMax="9.5" valueMin="7.5">7.5–9.5 µm</quantity>
. Axial area linear, narrow, expanding into a large, panduriform central area. Central area forming well-defined fascia, expanding to the valve margins. Terminal area clearly distinguishable, moderately large, triangular in shape. Raphe linear, weakly lateral, with weakly pronounced, simple linear or small dot-like central pores. Central pores distantly spaced. Terminal pores of raphe barely discernible with LM, weakly pronounced, simple linear and abruptly terminated. Striae coarse, moderately to strongly radiate at the middle, becoming moderately to strongly convergent near valve ends. Striae evenly spaced throughout, 
<quantity box="[1270,1345,1140,1166]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.651" metricValueMax="1.778" metricValueMin="1.524" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" unit="in" value="6.5" valueMax="7.0" valueMin="6.0">6–7 in</quantity>
<quantity box="[1352,1431,1140,1166]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" unit="mm" value="10.0">10 µm</quantity>
. Interstriae quite narrower than the striae. Lineolae composing the striae quite densely spaced within a stria and not clearly discernible in LM.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1436,869,1552]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,351,1255,1281]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Distribution</emphasis>
:— 
<taxonomicName authorityName="A. Pavlov, Levkov, D. M. Williams &amp; Edlund" authorityYear="2013" box="[388,613,1256,1281]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Hippodonta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="crassa">
<emphasis box="[388,613,1256,1281]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Hippodonta crassa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has so far only been observed from Lake Tanganyika, East Africa. In the 
<typeStatus box="[194,244,1294,1320]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">type</typeStatus>
material it is very frequent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1436,869,1552]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,364,1333,1359]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Observations</emphasis>
:—With regard to the valve outline, the appearance of the striae and the shape of the central area 
<taxonomicName authorityName="A. Pavlov, Levkov, D. M. Williams &amp; Edlund" authorityYear="2013" box="[209,324,1372,1398]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Hippodonta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="crassa">
<emphasis box="[209,230,1372,1397]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[246,324,1372,1397]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">crassa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="var. costulatiformis" box="[550,1006,1372,1398]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Hippodonta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="variety" species="costulatiformis" variety="costulatiformis">
<emphasis box="[550,571,1372,1397]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[587,766,1372,1397]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">costulatiformis</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis box="[827,1006,1372,1397]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">costulatiformis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Lange-Bertalot, H. &amp; Metzeltin, D. &amp; Witkowski, A." box="[1023,1347,1372,1398]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" pagination="247 - 276" refId="ref27546" refString="Lange-Bertalot, H., Metzeltin, D. &amp; Witkowski, A. (1996) Hippodonta gen. nov. Iconographia Diatomologica 4: 247 - 276." type="journal article" year="1996">
Lange-Bertalot 
<emphasis box="[1214,1275,1372,1397]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">et al.</emphasis>
1996
</bibRefCitation>
: figs 1: 27–29; this study 
<figureCitation box="[370,508,1410,1436]" captionStart="FIGURES 27–63" captionStartId="37.[151,269,1738,1762]" captionTargetBox="[264,1323,194,1706]" captionTargetId="figure-52@37.[264,1323,194,1706]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="FIGURES 27–63: LM micrographs. Figs 27–44. Hippodonta latelanceolata (type material). Fig. 30. Complete frustule in girdle view. Figs 45–63. Hippodonta costulatiformis var. costulatiformis. Fig. 63. Complete frustule in girdle view. Scale bar = 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5071980" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5071980/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Figs 45–63</figureCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="A. Pavlov, Levkov, D. M. Williams &amp; Edlund" authorityYear="2013" box="[578,1003,1410,1436]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Hippodonta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="variety" species="costulatiformis" variety="densistriata">
<emphasis box="[578,599,1411,1436]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[615,797,1411,1436]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">costulatiformis</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis box="[860,1003,1411,1436]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">densistriata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1021,1160,1410,1436]" captionStart="FIGURES 69–95" captionStartId="39.[151,270,1125,1149]" captionTargetBox="[264,1323,194,1102]" captionTargetId="figure-49@39.[264,1323,194,1102]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="FIGURES 69–95: LM micrographs. Figs 69–83. Hippodonta costulatiformis var. densistriata (type material). Figs 82, 83. Images of complete frustule in girdle view. Figs 84–95. Hippodonta naviculiformis (type material). Scale bar = 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5071984" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5071984/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Figs 69–83</figureCitation>
) from Lake Prespa. In comparison to the latter two taxa, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="A. Pavlov, Levkov, D. M. Williams &amp; Edlund" authorityYear="2013" box="[577,695,1449,1475]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Hippodonta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="crassa">
<emphasis box="[577,598,1449,1474]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[615,695,1449,1474]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">crassa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has broader and coarser striae, in addition to the consistent panduriform shape of the central area. The central areas of 
<taxonomicName authority="var. costulatiformis" box="[880,1346,1488,1514]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Hippodonta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="variety" species="costulatiformis" variety="costulatiformis">
<emphasis box="[880,901,1488,1513]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[917,1100,1488,1513]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">costulatiformis</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis box="[1163,1346,1488,1513]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">costulatiformis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="A. Pavlov, Levkov, D. M. Williams &amp; Edlund" authorityYear="2013" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Hippodonta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="variety" species="costulatiformis" variety="densistriata">
<emphasis box="[1407,1428,1488,1513]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[151,327,1527,1552]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">costulatiformis</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis box="[384,522,1527,1552]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">densistriata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are weakly panduriform or mostly rectangular.
</paragraph>
